            <p>Portsmouth. N.H.<lb/>
                Aug<hi rend="sup">t</hi> 11&#47; 84<lb/></p>
            <p>My dear Mr.Marcus<lb/></p>
            <p>Many thanks for your<lb/> congratulatory letter of <del>the</del><lb/> July 20. which reached me<lb/> via St. <hi rend="underline">Johns</hi> today burying<lb/> Sergeant Israel at Camp<lb/> Clay&#91;.&#93; I omitted all portions<lb/> of the service which could<lb/> be in any way distasteful<lb/> to Jews&#91;.&#93; His burial in the<lb/> United States will take<lb/> place under his mother&#91;&#39;&#93;s<lb/> supervision at Kalamazoo&#91;.&#93;<lb/> He died or became <sic>unconcious</sic><lb/> in my arms&#8212;He was an<lb/> honor to your race<lb/></p>
            <p><sic>Sincerly</sic> Yours<lb/>
                sig  A.W. Greely<lb/>
                U S Army&#95;&#95;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>Portsmouth N.H.<lb/></p>
            <p>Lieutenant Greeley in answer to a communication<lb/> from Mr Alfred A. Marcus who expressed a wish<lb/> that the body of Sergeant Edward&#91;&#63;&#93; Israel<lb/> might be interred according to Jewish rites&#44; says&#58;<lb/> &#34;To day &#40;July 20&#41; in burying Sergeant Israel&#44;<lb/> I omitted in the service all portions which could<lb/> in any way be distasteful to Jews. The<lb/> burial at Kalamazoo was under the su<lb/>&#45;pervision of his mother. The young man<lb/> died unconscious in my arms. He was an<lb/> honor to the race of which you are a member.&#34;<lb/></p>
        </body>
